    tagline: 'The greatest pianist who ever lived and the inventor of the solo recital',
    intro: 'Franz Liszt was the first true superstar of classical music — a virtuoso pianist of superhuman ability whose performances caused women to faint and audiences to riot. Beyond his legendary pianism, he invented the symphonic poem, championed the music of others with extraordinary generosity, and composed works that pushed harmony to the very edge of tonality.',
    earlyLife: 'Born in Raiding, Hungary (now Austria), Liszt was a child prodigy who gave his first concert at age nine. His father moved the family to Vienna, where the young Franz studied with Carl Czerny (a student of Beethoven) and Antonio Salieri. By his teens, he was performing across Europe to rapturous acclaim, and a famous encounter with Beethoven reportedly ended with the old master kissing his forehead.',
    career: 'After years as the most celebrated concert pianist in history, Liszt retired from the stage in 1848 to focus on composition and teaching. In Weimar, he invented the symphonic poem — a new orchestral form inspired by literature and art. His generosity was legendary: he taught hundreds of students for free, championed the music of Wagner, Berlioz, and Grieg, and used his fame to promote countless younger composers.',
    legacy: 'Liszt\'s impact on music is immeasurable. He invented the symphonic poem, pioneered the solo recital format, and expanded piano technique beyond what anyone thought possible. His late works — spare, dissonant, and hauntingly modern — anticipated the atonality of the 20th century by decades. As a teacher and champion of other composers, he shaped the entire trajectory of Romantic music. Wagner, Debussy, Ravel, and Bartók all owed him a profound debt.',
