    tagline: 'The master of Italian opera.',
    intro: 'Giuseppe Verdi was the dominant figure in Italian opera for over half a century and one of the most important composers in the entire history of the art form. From his early "galley years" of relentless production to the refined masterpieces of his old age, Verdi transformed Italian opera from a vehicle for vocal display into a powerful medium of human drama. His 28 operas, along with his Requiem, remain central to the repertoire of every major opera house in the world.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on October 9 or 10, 1813, in Le Roncole, a small village near Busseto in the Duchy of Parma, Verdi came from a modest family of innkeepers and farmers. His talent was recognized early by the local merchant and music patron Antonio Barezzi, who financed his studies. Rejected by the Milan Conservatory at eighteen — a decision the institution would forever regret — Verdi studied privately with Vincenzo Lavigna, a composer at La Scala. He returned to Busseto as municipal music director before his operatic ambitions drew him back to Milan.',
    career: 'Verdi\'s career spanned an extraordinary six decades. His early "galley years" (1842–1850) saw him produce opera after opera at a relentless pace, establishing his reputation across Italy and beyond. The middle period — crowned by the trilogy of Rigoletto, Il Trovatore, and La Traviata — revealed a composer of unmatched dramatic instinct and melodic genius. After Aida, he seemed to retire, but was coaxed back by his librettist Boito to produce two final Shakespearean masterpieces: the tragic Otello and the comic Falstaff. Throughout his career, Verdi\'s music was intertwined with Italian national identity; his name itself became an acronym for the Risorgimento cause ("Vittorio Emanuele Re D\'Italia").',
    legacy: 'Verdi is the most frequently performed opera composer in the world. His works form the backbone of the Italian operatic tradition and are staged thousands of times each year across every continent. Beyond opera, his Requiem is a staple of the choral repertoire. His gift for melody, his understanding of the human voice, and his unfailing dramatic instinct set a standard that has never been surpassed. More than a composer, Verdi became a symbol of Italian unity and pride — a cultural hero whose music speaks to universal themes of love, sacrifice, jealousy, and redemption.',
