    id: 'puccini', fullName: 'Giacomo Puccini', years: '1858–1924', birthYear: 1858, deathYear: 1924,
    genre: 'Classical', nationality: 'Italian', era: 'Late Romantic',
    tagline: 'The supreme master of operatic emotion.',
    intro: 'Giacomo Puccini was the last great composer in the Italian operatic tradition and the foremost exponent of verismo opera. His twelve operas — particularly the quartet of La Bohème, Tosca, Madama Butterfly, and Turandot — are among the most frequently performed in the world, cherished for their soaring melodies, vivid orchestration, and devastating emotional power. Puccini possessed an unrivaled gift for creating characters and situations that move audiences to tears, laughter, and exhilaration.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on December 22, 1858, in Lucca, Tuscany, Puccini came from a dynasty of church musicians spanning five generations. He was expected to follow in this tradition, but a performance of Verdi\'s Aida in Pisa in 1876 ignited his passion for opera. With the help of a scholarship from Queen Margherita and a stipend from his great-uncle, he enrolled at the Milan Conservatory in 1880, where he studied under Amilcare Ponchielli and Antonio Bazzini. His graduation piece, the <em>Capriccio sinfonico</em>, attracted favorable attention from critics.',
    career: 'Puccini was a perfectionist who composed relatively few operas but lavished extraordinary care on each one. Unlike the prolific Verdi, he spent years searching for the right subjects and refining his librettos through countless revisions. His orchestration was brilliantly innovative, absorbing influences from Debussy, Wagner, and even Stravinsky while remaining unmistakably his own. His heroines — Mim&igrave;, Tosca, Cio-Cio-San, Li&ugrave; — are among the most vivid and sympathetic characters in all of opera, and his arias ("Che gelida manina," "Vissi d\'arte," "Nessun dorma") have transcended the operatic stage to become part of global popular culture.',
    legacy: 'Puccini is the most performed opera composer of the 21st century. His works consistently top box-office charts at opera houses from New York to Tokyo, and his arias are among the most recorded vocal pieces in history. "Nessun dorma" from Turandot became a global phenomenon after Luciano Pavarotti\'s performances, and La Bohème inspired the hit musical Rent. His genius lay in combining sophisticated orchestral writing with an unfailing instinct for human emotion — creating works that are at once theatrically thrilling and deeply moving. He was the last in the great line of Italian opera composers, and no one has truly taken his place.',
