    tagline: 'The revolutionary who transformed opera into music drama.',
    intro: 'Richard Wagner was one of the most influential — and controversial — figures in the history of Western music. A composer, conductor, theatre director, and polemicist, he transformed opera from a collection of set pieces into a continuous, unified art form he called <em>Gesamtkunstwerk</em> (total work of art). His innovations in harmony, orchestration, and dramatic structure influenced virtually every composer who came after him, and his works remain among the most monumental achievements in all of music.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on May 22, 1813, in Leipzig, Saxony, Wagner grew up in a theatrical family — his stepfather Ludwig Geyer was an actor and painter. Young Richard was captivated by the works of Beethoven and Weber, and largely self-taught as a musician. He studied briefly at the University of Leipzig and with Thomaskantor Christian Theodor Weinlig, who gave him a thorough grounding in counterpoint. By his early twenties, he had secured conducting posts at provincial opera houses in Würzburg, Magdeburg, and Riga, all the while nurturing his ambition to compose grand operas of his own.',
    career: 'Wagner\'s career was marked by towering ambition, financial chaos, political exile, and ultimate triumph. After early conventional operas, he developed his revolutionary concept of <em>Musikdrama</em> — continuous music driven by an intricate web of leitmotifs (recurring musical themes associated with characters, objects, and ideas). The mammoth Ring Cycle, composed over 26 years, remains the most ambitious work in operatic history: four interconnected operas totaling some 15 hours of music. Tristan und Isolde pushed harmony to its limits, while Parsifal created an entirely new genre of sacred theatre. Wagner even designed and built his own opera house at Bayreuth, where his works continue to be performed in an annual festival that draws devotees from around the world.',
    legacy: 'Wagner\'s impact on Western music is immeasurable. His harmonic innovations — particularly the unresolved "Tristan chord" — opened the door to chromaticism, atonality, and ultimately the entire trajectory of 20th-century music from Mahler and Strauss through Schoenberg. His concept of the <em>Gesamtkunstwerk</em> influenced not only opera but also cinema, with filmmakers from Eisenstein to Lucas citing his ideas about the union of music, drama, and visual spectacle. The Bayreuth Festival remains one of the most prestigious cultural events in the world, with waiting lists stretching years. Wagner\'s music continues to provoke, overwhelm, and transform audiences more than a century after his death.',
