    tagline: 'The first true jazz superstar',
    intro: 'Louis Daniel Armstrong — universally known as "Satchmo" or "Pops" — was an American trumpeter, vocalist, and entertainer whose influence on jazz is unparalleled. He single-handedly transformed jazz from a collective folk music into an art form centered on brilliant solo improvisation. His gravelly voice, beaming smile, and virtuosic trumpet playing made him the most recognized jazz musician in the world and one of the most influential figures in all of American music.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on August 4, 1901, in a desperately poor neighborhood of New Orleans known as "the Battlefield," Louis Armstrong grew up surrounded by the sounds of brass bands, blues, and ragtime. At age eleven, he was sent to the Colored Waif\'s Home for Boys after firing a pistol in the air on New Year\'s Eve, where he received formal music instruction and learned the cornet. After his release, he sought out King Oliver, the leading cornetist in New Orleans, who became his mentor. By his late teens, Armstrong was playing on Mississippi riverboats and building a reputation as the most exciting young horn player in the city.',
    career: 'Armstrong\'s Hot Five and Hot Seven recordings (1925–1928) are among the most important in all of recorded music. Tracks like "West End Blues" and "Potato Head Blues" demonstrated a level of trumpet virtuosity and emotional depth previously unheard in jazz. He invented scat singing, popularized the jazz solo, and influenced every jazz musician who came after him. In later decades, he became a beloved global ambassador for American culture, touring tirelessly with his All Stars sextet and appearing in over 30 films. His warmth, humor, and genius made jazz accessible to millions worldwide.',
    legacy: 'Louis Armstrong\'s impact on music extends far beyond jazz. He pioneered scat singing, established the jazz solo as the genre\'s primary mode of expression, and influenced everyone from Bing Crosby to Miles Davis. His recordings are in the Grammy Hall of Fame, and his home in Queens is now a National Historic Landmark and museum. "What a Wonderful World" remains one of the most played and beloved songs on earth. New Orleans International Airport was renamed Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport in 2001, and his birthday is celebrated as a civic holiday in the city.',
