    genre: 'Jazz', nationality: 'American', era: 'Bebop / Hard Bop',
    tagline: 'The architect of modern jazz piano',
    intro: 'Thelonious Sphere Monk was an American jazz pianist and composer whose utterly distinctive style — built on angular melodies, jagged rhythms, and startling use of dissonance and silence — made him one of the most original voices in the history of music. A founding architect of bebop alongside Charlie Parker and Dizzy Gillespie, Monk composed some of the most enduring standards in the jazz repertoire, including "\'Round Midnight," the most recorded jazz composition of all time. He is the second-most-recorded jazz composer after Duke Ellington.',
    earlyLife: 'Born on October 10, 1917, in Rocky Mount, North Carolina, Thelonious Monk moved with his family to the San Juan Hill neighborhood of Manhattan at age four. He began playing piano at age six, largely self-taught, though he briefly studied at Juilliard. As a teenager he toured with an evangelist, playing organ and accompanying gospel singing, which gave him a deep feel for the blues and the church. By his late teens, he was a regular at Harlem\'s rent parties and jam sessions, developing the unconventional technique and harmonic language that would become his signature.',
    career: 'As house pianist at Minton\'s Playhouse in Harlem from 1941, Monk was at the epicenter of bebop\'s creation. But while Parker and Gillespie achieved quick fame, Monk\'s music was considered too strange for mainstream audiences. His Blue Note recordings (1947–1952) were critically praised but commercially unsuccessful. The turning point came in 1957, when he regained his cabaret card and began a legendary residency at the Five Spot Cafe with John Coltrane. The engagement ran for months and transformed both musicians. Monk finally received wide recognition in the 1960s, touring internationally with his quartet and recording prolifically for Columbia Records.',
    legacy: 'Thelonious Monk is one of the most important composers in jazz history. "\'Round Midnight" is the single most recorded jazz composition ever written, and tunes like "Straight, No Chaser," "Blue Monk," and "Epistrophy" are essential standards. His uncompromising originality — once seen as eccentric — is now understood as visionary. He was posthumously awarded a Pulitzer Prize Special Citation in 2006 and inducted into the North Carolina Music Hall of Fame. The Thelonious Monk Institute of Jazz (now the Herbie Hancock Institute of Jazz) continues to support jazz education worldwide in his name.',
