    id: 'chet-baker', fullName: 'Chet Baker', years: '1929–1988', birthYear: 1929, deathYear: 1988,
    genre: 'Jazz', nationality: 'American', era: 'Cool Jazz',
    tagline: 'The Poet of Cool Jazz',
    intro: 'Chet Baker was an American trumpeter and vocalist whose fragile, intimate style made him one of the most distinctive voices in jazz. With a sound often described as "cool" and "lyrical," Baker stripped jazz down to its emotional essence, favoring understatement over virtuosic display. His version of My Funny Valentine became one of the most recognizable recordings in jazz history, and despite a life marked by personal turmoil, his musicianship remained hauntingly beautiful to the end.',
    earlyLife: 'Born Chesney Henry Baker Jr. on December 23, 1929, in Yale, Oklahoma, Chet grew up in a musical family — his father was a guitarist. The family moved to Glendale, California, where young Chet began playing trumpet in school bands. He had little formal training, learning largely by ear. After dropping out of high school, he enlisted in the U.S. Army in 1946 and played in the 298th Army Band in Berlin. Following his discharge, he briefly attended El Camino College before being drawn fully into the West Coast jazz scene in Los Angeles.',
    career: 'Baker\'s career began spectacularly when he joined Gerry Mulligan\'s pianoless quartet in 1952, a group that helped define West Coast cool jazz. His warm, breathy trumpet tone and understated phrasing stood in contrast to the fiery bebop of the East Coast. In 1954, his album Chet Baker Sings revealed a fragile, whispery vocal style that captivated audiences. His playing was characterized by economy — where others played many notes, Baker played few, each one perfectly placed and emotionally weighted. After a devastating assault in 1964 that cost him his teeth, he painstakingly rebuilt his embouchure and returned with an even more poignant, weathered sound that many consider his finest work.',
    legacy: 'Chet Baker remains one of the most iconic figures in jazz — a symbol of both the music\'s beauty and its contradictions. His intimate, less-is-more approach to trumpet and vocals influenced musicians from Art Farmer to Ambrose Akinmusire. The 1988 documentary Let\'s Get Lost, nominated for an Academy Award, cemented his legend as a tragic romantic figure. His recordings continue to be discovered by new generations, and My Funny Valentine remains one of the most streamed jazz recordings of all time. Baker proved that vulnerability and restraint could be just as powerful as virtuosity.',
