    id: 'muddy-waters', fullName: 'Muddy Waters', years: '1913–1983', birthYear: 1913, deathYear: 1983,
    genre: 'Blues', nationality: 'American', era: 'Chicago Blues',
    tagline: 'The Father of Modern Chicago Blues who electrified the Delta and gave birth to rock and roll',
    intro: 'Born McKinley Morganfield in rural Mississippi, Muddy Waters took the raw acoustic Delta blues of the South and transformed it with electric amplification on the stages of Chicago. His band template — electric guitar, harmonica, bass, piano, and drums — became the blueprint for every blues and rock band that followed.',
    earlyLife: 'Muddy Waters was born on April 4, 1913, in Issaquena County, Mississippi, and raised by his grandmother in Clarksdale after his mother died when he was three. He earned his childhood nickname playing in muddy creeks near the cabin. By his teens he was playing harmonica and guitar, deeply influenced by Son House and Robert Johnson, absorbing the Delta blues tradition at Saturday night fish fries and juke joints.',
    career: 'After moving to Chicago in 1943, Muddy Waters plugged in his guitar and created a new sound — loud, electrified, and urgent. Signed to Chess Records, he scored a string of hits through the 1950s that defined the Chicago blues. His band featured legends like Little Walter on harmonica, Otis Spann on piano, and Jimmy Rogers on guitar. By the late 1950s, British musicians like the Rolling Stones and Eric Clapton were studying his records note by note, launching the blues revival that reshaped popular music.',
    legacy: 'Muddy Waters is the single most important link between the acoustic Delta blues and modern electric blues and rock. He won six Grammy Awards and was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1987. His influence is immeasurable: the Rolling Stones, Led Zeppelin, Jimi Hendrix, Eric Clapton, and virtually every blues and rock artist since owes a debt to his electrified vision. The Chicago blues sound he pioneered remains a living tradition.',
